(1) The pre-existing retained austenite in the investigated 5Mn steel enhanced the reversed austenite
nucleation number during heating of the welding thermal cycle and led to the relatively small
grain size in simulated CGHAZ and FGHAZ.
(2) Austenite growth dominantly took place in the heating process and there was almost no austenite
growth in the cooling process above peak temperature during the simulated welding thermal
cycle. Therefore, the relatively small size was found in CGHAZ.
(3) The higher transformation rate was measured to be a maximumof 0.98 in the simulated FGHAZ
and a maximum of 0.60 in the simulated CGHAZ. Thus, a 10~11% austenite was retained
(4) Compared to CGHAZ with the larger grain size, the impact toughness in ﬁne grain FGHAZ was
not signiﬁcantly improved. This was due to the transformation of relatively harder martensite
and the TRIP effect during the impact test in simulated FGHAZ. Therefore, howto retain austenite
will be the future work of how to improve impact toughness of HAZ.
